#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Unusual Attitudes and Emergencies",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 3 — Lesson 11 | E16 + E10 check",
  author: "C.Moroney",
  version: "v1.0.0",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Unusual Attitudes and Emergencies]

,aim: [
Confirm E10 (Scenario Based Stalling) competency to S standard under student-as-PIC conditions, develop correct recovery from nose-high and nose-low unusual attitudes, manage in-flight emergency scenarios, and reinforce the ADM framework introduced in Lesson 9.
]

,overview: [
Lesson 11 has two distinct components: an E10 confirmation check and the introduction of E16 (Unusual Attitudes and Emergencies).

The E10 check is entirely student-led. The student completes HASSELL, briefs the stalling sequence, and executes scenario stalls without instructor input. The ceiling requirement for E10 (>3500 ft AGL) applies to the entire lesson. The instructor is a silent observer throughout the E10 check. If E10 is assessed as NC, the instructor notes this in the training record and continues to E16 for the lesson — remediation for E10 is scheduled as a separate flight before the area solo suitability assessment. The E16 result is independent.

The ADM framework is explicitly introduced in this lesson as a second exposure — the same framework from Lesson 9, now applied to novel in-flight emergency scenarios. This second exposure is deliberate: the student should recognise the framework as a general tool, not a PSL-specific tool. The instructor explicitly references Lesson 9 when introducing ADM in the context of E16.

E16 content is new. The instructor demonstrates unusual attitude recoveries and emergency scenarios; the student practices them. The student-as-PIC philosophy is maintained: the student handles all trained portions; the instructor assumes the instructor role only for new E16 material.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Describe the nose-high unusual attitude: causes, recognition (high pitch, low airspeed, approaching stall), recovery sequence
- Describe the nose-low unusual attitude: causes, recognition (low pitch, high airspeed, high descent rate), recovery sequence
- Explain why rolling wings level must precede backpressure in a nose-low recovery — reinforcing the spiral dive principle from E9
- Explain various in-flight failure procedures: engine fire, cabin fire, smoke and fumes; immediate actions for each from memory
- Apply the ADM framework to novel in-flight problems: Time → Assess → Predict → Evaluate; explicitly link to the PSL application from Lesson 9
- Describe trim failure and partial control restriction management

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Execute E10 (Scenario Based Stalling) to S standard without instructor input: HASSELL, turning stall, go-around stall prevention, EFATO stall scenario
- Recover from a nose-high unusual attitude: push (reduce AoA), full power if needed, roll wings level, establish controlled flight
- Recover from a nose-low unusual attitude: close throttle, roll wings level, ease out of the dive — wings level before backpressure
- Execute fire and smoke/fumes immediate actions from memory
- Identify a failed instrument and adapt the LARI scan
- Manage the aircraft with a simulated partial control restriction
- Apply ADM to a novel scenario described by the instructor

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [ADM] Explicit second exposure: apply Time → Assess → Predict → Evaluate to novel emergencies; reference the PSL application from Lesson 9; brief this connection before flight
- [TEM] Identify the scenarios that produce unusual attitudes: task overload, distraction, spatial disorientation; brief mitigations before flight
- [HF] Proprioceptive and vestibular illusions: the body is not a reliable attitude reference; use the horizon; brief for the nose-low scenario specifically
- [CRM] Brief each emergency scenario before entering; confirm control handover procedure for this lesson
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aerodynamics — spiral dive recognition and recovery *(Pg 106)* — revision from E9
- Aerodynamics — load factor, dynamic stall *(Pg 165, 173)*
- Human Factors — disorientation, vestibular cues *(Pg 20)*
- Human Factors — undesired aircraft states, ADM, countermeasures *(Pg 44, 48, 51)*
- Human Factors — stress and fatigue *(Pg 36–40)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 35 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Scenarios that produce unusual attitudes: distraction, task overload, inadvertent cloud, spatial disorientation; brief mitigations
- [HF] Proprioceptive illusions: the body tells the brain the aircraft is level when it is not; disorientation is genuine and rapid; trust instruments first, then the horizon

*E10 Check — Student Led* (5 minutes)
- Confirmation of standard only; no ground instruction for E10 is provided
- Student executes HASSELL and the stalling sequence without instructor input; instructor is silent
- If E10 is NC: note in training record; continue to E16; schedule remediation before area solo gate
- Decision rule: if the E10 check clearly requires more than 15 minutes, note NC and move to E16

*ADM — Second Exposure* (10 minutes)
- Reference Lesson 9: "We introduced ADM for the precautionary search decision. The same framework applies to every novel problem in the aircraft."
- Time: how much time is available to solve this problem? This question is always first — it determines the urgency of everything that follows
- Assess: what do I know? What do I not know? What are my resources?
- Predict: if I implement Plan A, what problems will I encounter?
- Evaluate: does the outcome match the prediction? If not, re-assess
- Example — smoke in the cockpit: Time (am I burning? how quickly is it spreading?); Assess (source? electrical? instruments affected?); Predict (if I land in 5 minutes, does that work?); Evaluate (is the smoke getting worse or better?)
- The ADM framework prevents rushing to a suboptimal decision under stress; "How much time?" is the phrase that stops panic
- Practical rule: if aircraft control is questionable, assess aircraft handling in the landing configuration at a safe altitude before committing to the approach

*Nose-High Unusual Attitude* (5 minutes)
- Recognition: high pitch attitude, airspeed reducing, AoA approaching critical, possible stall warning
- Connection to E7/E10: this is a precursor to the stall; recovery is a more urgent version of stall prevention
- Recovery: push (reduce AoA), apply power, roll wings level if bank is present; if steeply nose-high with low airspeed — push first; do not add power before reducing AoA

*Nose-Low Unusual Attitude* (5 minutes)
- Recognition: low pitch, airspeed increasing, high rate of descent, tight bank
- Connection to E9: this is the spiral dive recovery; the procedure is identical
- Recovery: close throttle, roll wings level, ease back once wings are level — not before
- Applying backpressure before wings are level tightens the spiral, increases structural load, and worsens the situation

*In-Flight Fire and Emergencies* (5 minutes)
- Engine fire: fuel selector off, mixture off, throttle closed, cabin heat off, land immediately
- Cabin fire: identify source; CO2 extinguisher if available; vents as appropriate; land immediately
- Smoke and fumes: ventilate cockpit; identify source; land as soon as practicable
- These are memory items: brief them on the ground before every flight that includes E16 exercises
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Student briefs the complete flight:*]
- Obtains NAIPS TAF/GAF/GPWT; checks BOM radar; briefs conditions — smooth air required; ceiling >3500 ft AGL for E10 check; confirms suitability
- Checks NOTAMs; briefs relevant items
- Reviews maintenance release; briefs instructor; instructor signs
- Briefs planned flight: departure, E10 check sequence (HASSELL minimum height), E16 exercises, return, EFATO plan
- Delivers pre-takeoff safety brief independently

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Receives brief; confirms conditions are suitable; confirms ceiling >3500 ft AGL
- Confirms HASSELL minimum height for E10 check
- Delivers E16 ground brief above; explicitly references ADM from Lesson 9
- Does not provide any content on the E10 check — this is student-led
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Student-as-PIC — Departure and Transit*]
Student handles all ground operations, startup, taxi, radio calls, and takeoff without prompting. Instructor is a silent observer.

#text(size:12pt)[*E10 Check — Student Led, Instructor as Silent Observer*]
The student completes and executes the E10 check entirely without instructor input:
- Student completes HASSELL check; instructor is silent
- Student executes: turning stall (30° AoB); go-around stall prevention; EFATO stall scenario
- Instructor observes and records silently; S or NC
- *If E10 is NC*: instructor does not intervene or comment until the debrief; continues to E16; schedules remediation note in training record
- *If E10 takes more than approximately 15 minutes of the session*: instructor signals transition to E16; records E10 as NC

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor Assumes Instructor Role — E16 New Material*]

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- *Nose-high unusual attitude*: Instructor creates the attitude using a realistic entry (e.g. clipboard accidentally applied to trim); demonstrates recovery; patter each action
- *Nose-low unusual attitude*: Instructor creates the attitude; patter recognition cues; demonstrates recovery — throttle, wings level, ease back
- *In-flight fire (simulated)*: Instructor calls "engine fire"; narrates immediate actions; patter sequence
- *Smoke/fumes (simulated)*: Instructor calls "smoke in cockpit"; narrates actions and ventilation

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice — E16*]
Instructor returns to observer role after demonstrations.
- *Unusual attitude practice*: Instructor creates attitude while student is heads-down on a task; student detects and applies correct recovery — nose-high wings level, nose-high with bank, nose-low wings level, nose-low with bank
- *Fire simulation*: Instructor calls scenario; student executes from memory; narrates each action
- *Smoke/fumes simulation*: Student identifies and narrates actions
- *Trim failure simulation*: Instructor applies trim deflection without comment; student identifies, compensates, narrates
- *Instrument failure*: Instructor covers an instrument; student identifies failure and adapts LARI scan
- *ADM scenario task*: "You are at 3500 ft in the training area and smoke is coming from behind the instrument panel. Apply the ADM framework — walk me through Time, Assess, Predict, Evaluate."

#text(size:12pt)[*Student-as-PIC — Return*]
Student conducts return transit, circuit join, and landing independently.
]

,common_errors:[
- *Pulling back before wings level in nose-low recovery*: The most common and dangerous error in this exercise — level wings first, without exception; reinforce every time.
- *Delay in fire action*: Fire immediate actions are memory items — they must be drilled on the ground before every flight that includes fire simulation.
- *ADM skipped in favour of immediate action*: For novel situations, "How much time?" must be asked before a solution is implemented; reinforce the framework.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Leads Debrief* (10 min): Student reports E10 check self-assessment; reviews each E16 scenario; self-assesses recovery sequences and ADM application.
- *Instructor Supplements* (10 min):
  - E10 result stated clearly: S or NC with specific evidence
  - If NC: explain deficiency; confirm remediation flight before area solo gate; E16 result unaffected
  - E16 result: P or S with specific comments per scenario
  - ADM application: was Time asked before solutions were proposed?
- *Theory Check* (5 min): Student states nose-low recovery sequence from memory; explains why backpressure must wait until wings are level.
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework. L12 is the area solo suitability assessment.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E10 Check — Recorded separately*]
- *S standard confirmed*: Turning stall recovery ≤300 ft, rudder on wing drop without prompting; go-around stall prevention correct; EFATO stall scenario managed; HASSELL completed — recorded as S confirmed in Phase 3
- *NC*: Specific deficiency noted; remediation flight scheduled before area solo gate; E16 result unaffected

#text(size:12pt)[*E16 (Unusual Attitudes and Emergencies)*]

#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to Lesson 12*]
- *Nose-high recovery*: Pushes forward and levels wings; may apply light backpressure before fully level with manageable result
- *Nose-low recovery*: Closes throttle; levels wings before significant backpressure; height loss manageable
- *Fire actions*: Executes from memory with minor sequencing error
- *ADM*: Framework applied with some prompting; Time question asked with guidance

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required for area solo gate*]
- *Nose-high recovery*: Correct sequence promptly; no stall; controlled; no instructor input
- *Nose-low recovery*: Throttle closed; wings levelled before backpressure; height loss ≤500 ft; no instructor input
- *Fire actions*: Memory items executed correctly and promptly in correct sequence without prompting
- *Smoke/fumes*: Identifies and manages without prompting; correct land decision
- *Trim/control failure*: Identifies and compensates correctly without prompting
- *ADM*: Always asks Time first before proposing solutions; applies framework to novel scenarios without prompting

- *Outcome*: E10 check recorded as S or NC. E16 recorded as P or S with specific comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible; ceiling >3500 ft AGL (E10 requirement); smooth air essential; wind <25 knots
- *Altitude*: E10 check above 2500 ft AGL; E16 unusual attitude exercises above 2500 ft AGL; recoveries complete above 2000 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: All exercises clearly briefed; HASSELL before E10 check; brief nose-high maximum angle and nose-low maximum airspeed before flight
- *TEM*:
  - E10 check: instructor is observer but safety-ready; take control at first sign of incipient spin or minimum height approach
  - Nose-low exercise: brief maximum airspeed before instructor intervenes; specify in knots before the flight
  - Fire simulation: do not actually close the fuel selector in flight; brief the simulation distinction before departure
  - Monitor for spatial disorientation after unusual attitude recovery; allow reorientation before continuing
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 106, 165, 170–173 (spiral dive, load factor, spin entry and recovery)
  - Human Factors: Pg 20, 44, 48, 51 (disorientation, undesired aircraft states, countermeasures)
  - Human Factors: Pg 36–40 (stress, fatigue)
- Memorise the fire and smoke/fumes immediate action sequences before Lesson 12
- Prepare for Lesson 12 (Area Solo Suitability Assessment):
  - Review all Phase 3 elements: E9, E10, E14a, E14b, E15, E16
  - Confirm theory exam status: BAK, Air Legislation, Human Factors
  - Review ERSA for YSPT
  - Review ABCDEF sequence from memory
- Reflect:
  - "What is the single most important action in recovering from any nose-low unusual attitude? Why must it happen before everything else?"
  - "You are flying in the training area and the oil pressure drops to zero. Using the ADM framework: how much time do you have? What do you assess? What do you predict? How do you evaluate?"
]
)

